The Breach of Oathes is a thing over common amongst our Kings. So that the Prophet doth give us a Caution,Mr. Prynnes Sov. Parl. part 2. p. 37. Ibid. par. 2. p. 55.
O put not your trust in Princes, Psal. 146.3. Surely men of high degree are a Lye, to be laid in the Ballances lighter then Vanity, Psal. 62.9. both in their Oathes and Promises. Anno 1375. 50. Ed. 3. it was ordained that certaine Bishops, Earles, and Lords, should governe both the King and Kingdome; the King being then in his Dotage, and unable to governe himselfe or the Kingdome, because the King was growne old, and wanted such Governours. Salvares est, crubescit. Well fare this good man, he hath some modestie yet; he will not put his Majestie to an Open Shame: he doth but onely implie that our King is guiltie of Common Breach of Oaths and Promises; and that he is in his Dotage, not able to Governe his Kingdome, nor Himselfe. And therefore hee wanteth such Governours as prudent Mr. Prynne shall appoint. But exerte, & aperte;
heare him next speaking Plaine English, to some purpose.

Sov. of Parl. part 2. p. 2. There will be (saith he) a Desolation of our Kingdome, if there be not a speedy honourable and safe Accommodation. Appears not this man to be an excellent Patriot? a Pacificus? a blessed Peace-maker? yet in contradiction to this, he perswades the people, that safe peace is impossible, both for and from the Kings party. A safe peace must proceed from the Kings Protestations, or from an Act of Oblivion. That the people cannot depend upon His Majesties publike printed Promises and Protestations: he doth dispute it in foure or five folio's together: wherein his 4. Argument and 34. folio, he discovers his mind in these modest and mannerly words: Because our Kings, Iohn, Edward and Richard 2. having got possession of the Castles by Accommodation;
Brake their Vowes— shall wee dreame of a new world in this Dissembling age, when King-Craft is improved to the uttermost? Mr. Prynne ibid. p. 27. ad 34. Part 1. pag. 10 And that hee may make even an Act of Oblivion distrusted also, he tells the people, That Edward the second to avoid danger, passed an Act of Indemnitie, but the Barons returned neither merrie nor secure. On the other side, he puts the Kings partie in Despaire of any peace from the Parliament.Mr. Prynne Appendix p. 216.
All they (saith he) that joine with the Popish Malignant partie— certainly such Vnnaturall Monsters, such trayterous Iudasses, such execrable infamous Apostats, can expect no other remuneration of their perfidiousnesse, but the Ruine of their Credi • s, the Detestation of their Persons,part 2. Epist. part 3. Epist. Part 3. p. 70. Part 3. p. 133. Part 4 p. 35. Append. 217. Mr. Prynne part 3. p. 147. vel 149. Part 4. Epist. the Confiscation of their Estates, and the Extirpation of their Families. Thus this Boutefeu in one place seemeth to cast Water, but in others he doth cast Oyle on our Fire of Warre: he talketh of peace, but prepareth his Brethren to Battle. And indeed the maine drift of all his Bookes is against peace; as may appeare by these places in the Margine. Vpon whose Head then will that Bolt fall, which this wise man shot towards Heaven in his dreadfull Imprecation? Let Gods curse and mens for ever rest upon all those who are in love with any Warre, especially with Civill Warre within their owne dearest Countries bowels. Moreover, in his Epistle before rhe 4 part, he protesteth, I alwayes have been, and ever shall be an Honourer and Defender of Kings and their Monarchie: but in the very first page of that Booke hee maketh as deepe, but Contradictorie Protestation: I shall cleare the Parliaments just right in ordering the Militia by Sea and Land; in disposing the Ships and Forts;Mr. Prynnes Soveraignty, part 4. pa. 1. in concluding Warre and Peace; in placing and displacing the great Officers and Privie Councellours; yea in Regulating the Kings Houshold and meniall Servants. What is left to his Majestie, the Monarch, by this man who professeth himselfe such an Honourer of Monarchie?

This maketh me to beleeve in part, that in part this Master-piece of Rome was framed in the Head-piece of Mr. William Prynne, but I am prae-judged:

 if I deeme this an Imposture, I am an Infidell;
