If any will wash the Black-Moore white, and excuse M. Prynne, that he delivereth all these Examples, onely historically;
                     ibid. part 1. p. 10. but that he determineth nothing Dogmatically. Credat Iudaeus Appella, M. Prynne himselfe (I am perswaded) doth not believe it: Let himselfe say: Wherefore doth he then print such Presidents, under such a Title, as, The Soveraigne Power of Parliaments? Consider withall his Epiphonema,

                     ibid. p. 8. his additionall Approbation to the Trayterous Murder of King Edward 2. in Barkley Castle. And so (saith M. Prynne) the sicknesse and wounds, which this Common-wealth susteined by his Ill Reigne, upon the change of the Physitian, received not onely health, but beauty also and ornament: and he applaudeth that stile which was then given to those bloudy Tragedies: that they were called Zelatores Reipublicae, the Zelots of the English Republike. Notwithstanding, heare this loyall Subject deliver his definitive sentence of the Kings Majesty.
